notes: Standing dead tim- ber was classified as "standing dead" regardless of the condition of the wood. Dead wood >3 cm in di- ameter on the forest floor surface was placed in one of three decay classes on the basis of penetrability. A pointed metal rod 0.5 cm in diameter was pushed firm- ly into the wood. Decay classes were defined as: ''slightly decayed''-penetration <0.5 cm; "moder- ately decayed''-penetration 0.5 cm to the radius of the bole; "advanced decay" -penetration through the bole. Since decay state varied along an individual bole, classification was determined by the decay state of >50% of the bole.

For CWD, we used five decay classes, from relatively sound wood as decay class 1 to detritus with the most advanced decay as class 5. We distinguished decay classes in the field by the presence of bark and branches, the degree of sapwood degradation, the soundness of the heartwood, and the presence of moss and fungi; this study made fine-scale differentiations between caorse wood debris and fine woody debris;
